begin;

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Surgery for all nodules"},{"label":"B","text":"Thyroid Nodule Evaluation (ATA 2015)"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore — palpable nodules common"},{"label":"D","text":"Random biopsy without US"},{"label":"E","text":"Only TSH test"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Thyroid Nodule Evaluation (ATA 2015): (1) **Initial workup**: TSH + thyroid US for all palpable / incidentally discovered nodules; (2) **TSH-based approach**: - TSH **low/suppressed** → radioiodine scan (hot nodule rarely malignant, hyperthyroid Rx if toxic); - TSH **normal/elevated** → US characterization; (3) **US classification (ACR TI-RADS or ATA sonographic patterns)** stratifies malignancy risk + biopsy threshold: - **TI-RADS 1-2 / Benign / Very low suspicion** — no FNA; - **TR3 / Low** — FNA if ≥ 2.5 cm or follow if ≥ 1.5 cm; - **TR4 / Intermediate** — FNA if ≥ 1.5 cm; - **TR5 / High suspicion** — FNA if ≥ 1.0 cm; - **High-risk features**: solid hypoechoic, microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller-than-wide, extrathyroidal extension, suspicious LN; (4) **FNA biopsy (US-guided)** — Bethesda system 6 categories: - **I** Non-diagnostic → repeat FNA; - **II** Benign → US surveillance 12-24 mo; - **III** AUS/FLUS → repeat FNA or molecular; - **IV** Suspicious for follicular neoplasm → lobectomy vs molecular; - **V** Suspicious for malignancy → surgery; - **VI** Malignant → surgery; (5) **Molecular testing** (Afirma, ThyroSeq, ThyGeNEXT/ThyraMIR) for indeterminate (Bethesda III, IV) — reduces unnecessary surgery; (6) **Treatment**: - **Benign nodule** — US surveillance + adjust intervals based on growth/changes; symptomatic / cosmetic → ethanol ablation / RF ablation / surgery; - **Differentiated thyroid CA (papillary > follicular)** — lobectomy vs total thyroidectomy ± LN dissection; RAI ablation selected; levothyroxine suppression; surveillance Tg + neck US; - **Medullary** — total thyroidectomy + central LN; calcitonin, CEA, RET mutation; - **Anaplastic** — aggressive, multimodal; - **Lymphoma, metastatic** — specific; (7) **Active surveillance** for low-risk papillary microcarcinoma (< 1 cm, well-differentiated) — alternative to surgery selected (Ito + others); (8) **Pediatric**: more likely malignant if found — refer endocrine + FNA threshold lower; (9) **Pregnancy**: FNA OK; defer surgery if possible to postpartum; RAI contraindicated; (10) **Family history**: MEN2 (medullary), FAP (PTC), Cowden — genetic considerations; (11) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + endocrinology + endocrine surgery + cytopathology + radiology + nuclear medicine

---

Thyroid nodule: TSH + US for all. TI-RADS or ATA pattern guides FNA threshold (size + features). Bethesda categorization → management. Molecular testing for indeterminate. Surgical pathology directed treatment. Active surveillance selected. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี — palpable thyroid nodule 1.8 cm, asymptomatic, normal TSH, no compression';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"IV antibiotic for all uncomplicated"},{"label":"B","text":"Acute Uncomplicated Diverticulitis (AGA 2015 + 2022)"},{"label":"C","text":"Surgery first episode"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid nuts/seeds long-term"},{"label":"E","text":"No colonoscopy"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Acute Uncomplicated Diverticulitis (AGA 2015 + 2022): (1) **Diagnosis**: CT contrast preferred imaging (also assesses complications — abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction); WBC + CRP; (2) **Classification**: uncomplicated vs complicated (abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction, peritonitis, hemorrhage); (3) **Treatment uncomplicated outpatient** (selected patients): - **Antibiotics — selective use** (AGA 2015 update — not all patients need): - Consider observation without antibiotics in mild uncomplicated patients (AVOD + DIABOLO trials — no benefit antibiotic over supportive); - Reasonable: hospitalize / antibiotic if immunocompromised, comorbidity, elderly, complicated, can''t tolerate PO, severe systemic; - If antibiotic — **amoxicillin-clavulanate** PO × 5-10 d (newer trials shorter courses) OR ciprofloxacin + metronidazole; - Hospital IV: ceftriaxone + metronidazole or pip-tazo; (4) **Diet**: clear liquid early, advance as tolerated; no evidence prolonged restriction; no need to avoid nuts, seeds, popcorn long-term (historical myth); (5) **Follow-up + colonoscopy after acute episode**: - **Routine colonoscopy 4-8 wk after recovery** for first episode in patients without recent colonoscopy — exclude malignancy (rates of CRC slightly elevated post-diverticulitis); evidence supports but some emerging modification for younger / clear-cut cases; (6) **Long-term management**: - **High-fiber diet** + adequate hydration — recurrence prevention; - **Physical activity** + weight; - **Avoid NSAIDs** (perforation risk); - **Smoking cessation**; - **Mesalamine** + rifaximin + probiotics — limited evidence; (7) **Surgery** (elective for recurrent or complicated, urgent for complications): - **Elective sigmoidectomy** — individualized based on recurrence frequency, severity, lifestyle impact, complicated episodes; previous threshold of 2 episodes no longer absolute (more individualized); - **Complicated abscess**: percutaneous drainage if > 4 cm; smaller may respond to antibiotics alone; - **Perforation / peritonitis** → urgent surgery (Hartmann''s procedure traditional, primary anastomosis emerging); (8) **Complications watch**: - **Abscess**; - **Perforation** (free air → emergency); - **Fistula** (colovesical most common — UTI, pneumaturia, fecaluria); - **Obstruction**; - **Hemorrhage** (separate diverticular bleed); (9) **Recurrence common** (~ 30%); (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + GI + surgery + radiology + IR (drainage) + dietitian

---

Acute uncomplicated diverticulitis: CT diagnosis. Outpatient OK selected — antibiotics selective (AGA 2015), often supportive sufficient. Colonoscopy 4-8 wk post for first. Long-term high-fiber + lifestyle. Surgery individualized. Watch complications. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 55 ปี — LLQ pain × 2 d + low-grade fever + bowel change; mild-mod tenderness, no peritoneal signs, no leukocytosis severe; CT shows uncomplicated sigmoid diverticulitis';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Ignore — anticoagulant"},{"label":"B","text":"Microscopic Hematuria Workup (AUA 2020)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single UA negative — done"},{"label":"D","text":"Antibiotic empirically"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait for gross hematuria"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Microscopic Hematuria Workup (AUA 2020): (1) **Diagnosis**: ≥ 3 RBC/HPF on properly collected midstream urine confirmed on 1 of 2 urinalyses; (2) **Risk stratification AUA 2020 (replaces prior age-based)**: - **Low risk**: women < 50, men < 40, never smoker, < 10 RBC/HPF, no risk factors → repeat UA within 6 mo; if hematuria persists → reclassify; - **Intermediate risk**: 50-60 yo women, 40-60 yo men, 10-30 pack-yr smoking, 11-25 RBC/HPF, other risk factors → cystoscopy + renal US; - **High risk** (this patient): > 60 yo, > 30 pack-yr smoker, > 25 RBC/HPF, gross hematuria → cystoscopy + CT urography (CTU) — best test for upper tract; (3) **Rule out first**: UTI (treat + repeat), exercise, menstruation, sexual activity, trauma, GU procedure recent; (4) **Workup**: - **Urinalysis** confirm; - **Urine culture** rule out UTI; - **Urine cytology** — limited utility primary; useful selected (high-risk + cytology positive → urgent workup); - **Imaging**: - **CT urography** — gold standard upper tract (high-risk); - **Renal US** + KUB — alternative if CT contraindication / pregnancy / younger; - **MRI urography** alternative; - **Cystoscopy** — bladder evaluation (>= intermediate risk); - **Cr / BUN, BP**; - **Proteinuria, dysmorphic RBC, casts** suggest glomerular cause → nephrology workup (BMP, UPC, ANA, complement, hepatitis serology, etc.); (5) **Causes**: - **Urologic** (workup priorities high-risk): malignancy (bladder, kidney, prostate, urethra), stones, BPH, infection, trauma, polycystic kidney; - **Nephrologic / glomerular**: IgA nephropathy, thin BM disease, Alport, glomerulonephritis (post-infectious, lupus, vasculitis), other; - **Other**: medications (rifampin, NSAIDs), exercise; (6) **Smoking cessation** — bladder cancer major risk; (7) **Follow-up negative workup**: repeat UA periodically (annual) — many resolve spontaneously; consider repeat workup if persistent + change in risk; nephrology referral if glomerular features; (8) **Bladder cancer high index suspicion** smoker + hematuria — don''t dismiss; (9) **Anticoagulation**: doesn''t excuse workup — anticoagulant-related hematuria still needs evaluation if persistent; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + urology + nephrology + radiology + smoking cessation

---

Microscopic hematuria: AUA 2020 risk-stratified workup. High-risk (smoker, > 60, > 25 RBC) → cystoscopy + CT urography. Rule out UTI/menstruation first. Glomerular features → nephrology. Smoking cessation. Don''t dismiss bladder CA. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 55 ปี — microscopic hematuria (5 RBC/HPF) ตอนทำ annual exam; no UTI; smoker × 30 yr; HT';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"MRI immediately for all"},{"label":"B","text":"Lumbar Radiculopathy / Sciatica Management (ACP + NASS)"},{"label":"C","text":"Long-term opioid"},{"label":"D","text":"Bed rest × 4 weeks"},{"label":"E","text":"Surgery first-line"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Lumbar Radiculopathy / Sciatica Management (ACP + NASS): (1) **Diagnosis**: history (radiating leg pain > back pain, dermatomal, exacerbated by Valsalva, sciatic stretch — SLR + crossed SLR), exam (neurologic — sensory, motor, reflexes); rule out cauda equina (saddle anesthesia, bladder/bowel) emergency; (2) **No imaging routinely first 4-6 wk** unless red flags or progressive neuro deficit; (3) **Conservative management 4-6 wk first** (most resolve within 3 mo without intervention): - Activity modification (avoid prolonged bed rest); - **NSAIDs** short-term; - **PT** — McKenzie method, core strengthening, neurodynamic mobilization; - **Education** + reassurance — favorable prognosis; - Heat / ice; - **Avoid opioids** as first-line (limited benefit + harms); - **Gabapentin / pregabalin** — modest evidence radicular pain (more for diabetic neuropathy); - **Oral steroids** — limited evidence for sciatica (METEOR trial — modest functional benefit); - **Topical agents**; - **Acupuncture** alternative; (4) **MRI lumbar** indicated for: - **Red flags** (cauda equina, malignancy, infection, fracture); - **Progressive neuro deficit**; - Failed conservative ≥ 6 wk + considering interventional/surgical; - Atypical / suspicious; (5) **Epidural steroid injection (ESI)**: - Modest short-term benefit for radicular pain (NASS); - Transforaminal or interlaminar; - Image-guided (fluoroscopy / US); - 1-3 typically, no more than 3/yr; - Risks: rare but serious (infection, hematoma, paralysis with cervical TF approach); (6) **Surgery indications**: - **Cauda equina** (emergent); - **Progressive motor deficit** (weakness); - **Refractory disabling pain ≥ 6-12 wk** + correlative imaging (microdiscectomy, decompression, sometimes fusion); - SPORT trial — surgery + conservative both effective long-term, surgery faster recovery; (7) **Yellow flags** (psychosocial chronicity risk): fear-avoidance, depression, work issues — address; (8) **Return to activity** + work modifications; (9) **Multimodal chronic** if persistent — CBT, multidisciplinary pain program; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + PT + pain medicine + spine surgery (ortho or neurosurgery) + behavioral health

---

Sciatica: rule out cauda equina. No imaging first 4-6 wk without red flags. Conservative (PT, NSAIDs, activity, education). MRI if red flags / refractory / progressive deficit. ESI selective. Surgery for emergent or refractory + correlative imaging. Yellow flags. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 45 ปี — radicular leg pain + numbness + L5 distribution × 4 wk; no red flags; conservative therapy failing';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No treatment — self-limited"},{"label":"B","text":"Bell''s Palsy Management (AAN 2012 + AAO-HNS 2013)"},{"label":"C","text":"Surgery first-line"},{"label":"D","text":"Antibiotic for all Bell''s palsy"},{"label":"E","text":"No eye care needed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Bell''s Palsy Management (AAN 2012 + AAO-HNS 2013): (1) **Diagnosis clinical**: acute (< 72 h) peripheral CN VII palsy involving forehead (unlike central — preserves forehead); often unilateral; can include hyperacusis, decreased taste anterior 2/3 tongue, decreased lacrimation, postauricular pain; (2) **Differential** — rule out before Bell''s palsy diagnosis: - **Central (stroke)** — preserves forehead, other neuro deficits; - **Lyme disease** — bilateral facial palsy, endemic area, tick exposure, classic erythema migrans (50%) → serology (high prevalence area), treat doxycycline; - **Ramsay Hunt syndrome (HZV)** — vesicles in ear canal, severe pain, sometimes hearing loss / vertigo → acyclovir + steroid + urgent ENT; - **Otitis media / mastoiditis**; - **Trauma / fracture**; - **Tumor** (slowly progressive, recurrent, complete + atypical features → MRI); - **Sarcoidosis, GBS, MS**; (3) **Workup**: clinical for typical; selected — Lyme serology endemic, HSV/VZV serology if vesicles, CBC, glucose, imaging if atypical/progressive/recurrent (MRI w/ contrast); (4) **Treatment — start within 72 h for best outcomes**: - **Prednisone 60 mg daily × 7 days then taper** — Class I evidence (Engstrom, Sullivan); improves probability complete recovery; - **Antiviral (acyclovir, valacyclovir)** — controversial, possible modest benefit added to steroid in severe cases (Class II); use combination if severe (House-Brackmann ≥ IV) per some guidelines; not effective alone; - **Eye care critical**: lubricating drops daytime, ophthalmic ointment + taping/patch nighttime, eye protection; ophthalmology if persistent (risk corneal abrasion + ulceration); - **Facial exercises / PT** — may help recovery; (5) **Prognosis**: - 70% complete recovery without treatment; - 85% with steroid; - Recovery 3 wk - 6 mo typically; - Persistent / synkinesis / facial spasm in 30%; - Worse prognosis: complete palsy, older, DM, HTN, taste loss, hyperacusis, postauricular pain severe; (6) **Refractory / no improvement**: - Refer ENT / neurology / facial nerve specialist; - Electrodiagnostic studies (ENoG, EMG) 5-21 days post-onset for prognostic + decision on intervention; - Surgical decompression — selected severe nonimprovement (controversial); - Botox + selective neurectomy for late synkinesis; - Facial reanimation surgery; (7) **Recurrent or bilateral** — investigate for underlying cause (Lyme, sarcoid, lymphoma, GBS); (8) **Pregnancy**: 3x higher; usually 3rd trimester / immediate postpartum; treatment + close monitoring; (9) **Patient education + emotional support**: facial appearance distressing; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + neurology + ENT + ophthalmology + PT + facial nerve specialist (refractory) + mental health if needed

---

Bell''s palsy: peripheral CN VII (forehead involved). Rule out central, Lyme, Ramsay Hunt. Treatment within 72 h: prednisone 60 mg × 7 d → taper. Antiviral selected for severe. Eye care critical. Prognosis good — most recover. Refractory specialist. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 35 ปี — acute unilateral facial weakness (forehead + face) × 1 d, decreased tear + taste, ปวดหลังหู; no other neuro deficit';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Antihistamine alone"},{"label":"B","text":"Anaphylaxis — Emergency (AAAAI + WAO 2020)"},{"label":"C","text":"Steroid alone"},{"label":"D","text":"Wait for symptoms to progress"},{"label":"E","text":"Subcutaneous epi only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Anaphylaxis — Emergency (AAAAI + WAO 2020): (1) **Diagnosis**: rapid-onset (minutes to hours) of skin/mucosa involvement + ≥ 1 of (respiratory, hypotension/end-organ, GI, syncope); OR hypotension/respiratory after known allergen exposure; (2) **TRIGGER first-line: IM epinephrine** — DO NOT DELAY: - **0.3-0.5 mg adults** (0.01 mg/kg, max 0.5 mg) **IM into vastus lateralis (anterolateral thigh)** — best absorption; - **0.15 mg child < 30 kg**; - **Repeat q 5-15 min** if no improvement (~ 30% need repeat); - **SC less effective** than IM; - **IV epinephrine drip** for refractory in monitored setting only — high arrhythmia risk if bolus; (3) **Position**: supine + legs elevated if hypotensive; left lateral if pregnant; sitting if dyspnea; (4) **Adjunct therapies (after epinephrine, not as substitute)**: - **Oxygen** + airway support; - **IV fluid** crystalloid bolus (20-30 mL/kg adult or 10-20 mL/kg child); - **H1 antihistamine** (diphenhydramine, cetirizine) — symptom relief skin only, NOT life-saving; - **H2 antihistamine** (famotidine) — symptom relief; - **Inhaled bronchodilator** (albuterol) for bronchospasm; - **Corticosteroid** (methylprednisolone 1-2 mg/kg IV) — debated efficacy in preventing biphasic, some evidence not helpful; given still by many; (5) **Refractory anaphylaxis**: - IV epinephrine drip; - Vasopressors (norepinephrine, vasopressin); - Glucagon 1-5 mg IV (especially beta-blocker-blocked patients); - Methylene blue refractory shock; (6) **Observation post-event**: - 4-6 hours typical mild; - 8-24+ hours severe; - **Biphasic reactions** in 5-20% (most within 4-6 h, can be up to 72 h); - Disposition based on clinical + risk; (7) **Discharge planning**: - **Epinephrine auto-injector prescription (≥ 2 devices)** — patient + family + school; - **Education** on use; - **Anaphylaxis action plan**; - **Trigger avoidance counseling**; - **Allergy referral** for trigger identification + further management; - **Medical alert** identification; - **No discharge without epinephrine prescription**; (8) **Allergist evaluation**: skin testing, specific IgE, oral food challenge, drug challenge (selected), component-resolved diagnostics; (9) **Immunotherapy / desensitization**: - **Venom immunotherapy** highly effective (hymenoptera); - **Oral immunotherapy (peanut — Palforzia)** FDA-approved 4-17 yo; - **Drug desensitization** for required medications; - Aeroallergen SCIT/SLIT for allergic rhinitis (may reduce systemic); (10) **Specific allergen counseling**: - **Food**: read labels, restaurant communication, school plans; - **Drug**: medical alert, listed on chart, alternatives; - **Insect**: avoidance, removal techniques; - **Latex**: occupational + medical; - **Idiopathic** anaphylaxis approach; (11) **Comorbidity**: asthma well-controlled (highest mortality), mast cell disease (mastocytosis); (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + ED + allergy/immunology + emergency response + family + school + pharmacy

---

Anaphylaxis: IM epinephrine IMMEDIATELY (0.3-0.5 mg vastus lateralis), repeat q 5-15 min if needed. Adjuncts (O2, IV fluid, H1/H2 antihistamine, bronchodilator, steroid) AFTER epi. Observation biphasic. Discharge with epi pen + plan + allergist referral. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 25 ปี — generalized hives + lip swelling + dyspnea + dizziness 15 min after eating shellfish; BP 90/60';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Fire family for refusing"},{"label":"B","text":"Vaccine Hesitancy Counseling (CDC + AAP + AAFP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Skip discussion entirely"},{"label":"D","text":"Random delayed schedule"},{"label":"E","text":"Lecture parents"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Vaccine Hesitancy Counseling (CDC + AAP + AAFP): (1) **Common parental concerns**: - Autism (myth from Wakefield retracted 1998 — extensively disproven across many large studies, > 1 million children); - Adverse events (most mild local, serious extremely rare per VAERS analyses); - ''Too many too soon'' (immune system handles thousands antigens daily; combined vaccines safe + well-studied); - Disease ''natural''; - Pharmaceutical motivations / mistrust; - Ingredients (aluminum, thimerosal — removed from most childhood vaccines 2001 in US except multi-dose flu); - Religious / philosophical beliefs; - COVID-related amplification of hesitancy; (2) **Communication approach evidence-based**: - **Presumptive (not participatory) approach** — recommend strongly + matter-of-factly: ''Today Sarah is due for MMR, varicella, and Hib'' (vs ''What do you want to do?''); evidence improves uptake; - **Motivational interviewing** for hesitant parents — open-ended, reflective listening, autonomy + collaboration; - **CASE approach** (Corroborate + About Me + Science + Explain/Advise) for serious concerns; - **Storytelling** + personal experiences; - **Address specific concerns** with evidence; - **Affirm parental love + caring**; - Avoid shaming; (3) **Specific autism + MMR**: - Wakefield 1998 fraudulent + retracted; - Over 1 million children studied across multiple meta-analyses — NO link; - Madsen, Hviid, others; - Real risks of measles (encephalitis, SSPE, death); recent outbreaks tragic; (4) **Vaccine schedule rationale**: - Each vaccine added based on disease burden + safety; - Combined / multiple at once safe + effective; - Delay = vulnerable window; - ''Alternative schedules'' not evidence-based; - Catch-up if behind; (5) **Vaccine adverse events**: - VAERS surveillance system; - VICP (Vaccine Injury Compensation Program) — no-fault compensation; - Risk-benefit favors vaccination; (6) **State + school requirements**: - School entry; - Religious + medical exemptions (variable by state); - Recent legislation tightening exemptions in some states (California SB 277); (7) **Resources for parents**: CDC vaccine info, AAP HealthyChildren.org, Children''s Hospital of Philadelphia Vaccine Education Center, Voices for Vaccines; (8) **Continuing the relationship**: - Don''t fire vaccine-hesitant families (controversial but recommended); - Continue to recommend each visit; - Build trust over time; - Document discussions + refusal forms; (9) **Disease re-emergence**: measles in US (declared eliminated 2000) recurring with under-vaccination; pertussis outbreaks; recent vaccine-preventable deaths preventable; (10) **Provider self-care**: hesitancy + refusal frustrating; institutional support; (11) **Public health response**: outbreak vaccination, contact investigation, community education; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + pediatric specialty + public health + community + school + media

---

Vaccine hesitancy: presumptive recommendation; MI for hesitant; address concerns with evidence (MMR-autism DISPROVEN); CASE approach. Continue relationship + document. Resources. Real disease risks (measles re-emergence). State/school requirements. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'พ่อแม่มาขอเลื่อนวัคซีน MMR ลูก 12 mo เพราะกังวลเรื่อง autism + กลัวการเจ็บปวดของลูก';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Ignore — hemorrhoids"},{"label":"B","text":"Rectal Bleeding (BRBPR) Workup (AGA + ACG)"},{"label":"C","text":"Skip colonoscopy"},{"label":"D","text":"Topical only"},{"label":"E","text":"Random imaging without rectal exam"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Rectal Bleeding (BRBPR) Workup (AGA + ACG): (1) **History**: characterize bleeding (with/separate from stool, amount, color), associated (pain, itching, discharge, mass, change in bowel habits, weight loss, family history CRC, IBD, smoking, NSAIDs); (2) **Exam**: general, abdominal, rectal (inspection + DRE — fissures, hemorrhoids, masses, sphincter tone); anoscopy (in office) for direct visualization; (3) **Causes BRBPR**: - **Hemorrhoids** — most common (internal painless, external painful if thrombosed); - **Anal fissure** — painful (tearing pain during BM, sentinel tag posterior most common, anterior may indicate trauma/Crohn''s); - **Polyps** — usually painless; - **Diverticular bleeding** (typically intermittent, painless, larger volume); - **Colitis** (IBD, ischemic, infectious, radiation); - **Colorectal cancer** (must rule out — esp older, anemia, weight loss); - **Anorectal trauma** (sexual, foreign body, instrumentation); - **Proctitis** (radiation, STI, IBD); - **Angiodysplasia** (typically right colon, painless); - **Solitary rectal ulcer**; (4) **Colonoscopy indications** (definitive): - **Age ≥ 40-45** with rectal bleeding (lower threshold age 40 emerging); - **Age < 40**: if persistent / recurrent, red flags (anemia, weight loss, family history, change in bowel habits), uncertain source — colonoscopy; if low risk + clear hemorrhoidal cause + responds to treatment → conservative + repeat eval if persistent; - **Anemia** present; - **Suspicion of malignancy**; - This patient at age 50 — colonoscopy indicated; (5) **Hemorrhoid management**: - **Conservative**: high-fiber diet + adequate fluid + sitz baths + topical (hydrocortisone, lidocaine); avoid straining + prolonged toilet; address constipation; - **Office procedures**: rubber band ligation (most effective), sclerotherapy, infrared coagulation; - **Surgery** (hemorrhoidectomy) for severe / Grade IV / refractory; - **Thrombosed external** — excision within 48-72 h if very painful; otherwise conservative; (6) **Anal fissure management**: - **Acute** — sitz bath + bulk laxative + topical analgesic; usually heal; - **Chronic** — topical nitroglycerin / diltiazem / nifedipine; botox; sphincterotomy if refractory; (7) **STI proctitis screening** for receptive anal sex + risk factors — NAAT chlamydia/gonorrhea + syphilis + HSV + HIV; treat per CDC; (8) **IBD considerations**: if persistent, systemic symptoms, atypical features → endoscopy + biopsy + workup; (9) **CRC age 45 screening start** USPSTF; this is opportunity for screening colonoscopy now; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + GI + colorectal surgery + dermatology selected + STI clinic if indicated

---

Rectal bleeding: characterize + DRE + anoscopy. Causes (hemorrhoid common, but rule out malignancy especially ≥ 45 yo). Colonoscopy threshold low (age ≥ 40-45 or red flags). Hemorrhoid + fissure conservative + procedures + surgery if refractory. STI proctitis screening. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี — bright red rectal bleeding (BRBPR) per stool × 2 wk + perianal discomfort, no weight loss, last colonoscopy 5 yr ago normal';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single 6-wk visit only"},{"label":"B","text":"Comprehensive 6-Week Postpartum Visit (ACOG 2018 + AAFP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Skip mental health"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid contraception discussion"},{"label":"E","text":"No future CV risk discussion"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Comprehensive 6-Week Postpartum Visit (ACOG 2018 + AAFP): (1) **ACOG 2018 update — postpartum care as ongoing process not single visit** — ''The 4th trimester'' framework: - Initial contact (in-person or phone) within 3 wk; - Comprehensive postpartum visit by 12 wk (not just 6); - Tailored to needs; - Many specific issues (chronic disease management, lactation, mental health, family planning) address ongoing; (2) **Comprehensive assessment domains**: - **Mental health**: PPD (EPDS, PHQ-9), anxiety, PTSD (especially traumatic birth, NICU baby, prior trauma), postpartum psychosis (rare, emergency), substance use, intimate partner violence screen; - **Reproductive health**: contraception, fertility, sexual function, dyspareunia, return of menses; - **Lactation**: support, problems, weaning decisions, medications during breastfeeding (LactMed); - **Physical recovery**: perineal/cesarean healing, urinary + fecal continence, prolapse, diastasis recti, pelvic pain; - **Chronic conditions**: BP (preeclampsia surveillance + future CV risk awareness — Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy = lifetime CV risk factor), diabetes (postpartum OGTT for GDM, T2DM monitoring), thyroid; - **Nutrition + activity + sleep**; - **Social + family**: childcare, return to work + workplace pumping rights (ACA), partner relationship, support system, financial; - **Health behaviors**: smoking, alcohol, substance use; - **Vaccination update**: Tdap if not in pregnancy, MMR if not immune (post-pregnancy as live), HepB, HPV catch-up, COVID, flu; (3) **Contraception counseling**: - LARC (IUD, implant) most effective; - **CDC US MEC**: < 21 d avoid combined hormonal (VTE); progestin OK; transition combined OK 21-42 d if no risk; - Tubal ligation, vasectomy options; - Breastfeeding considerations (LAM limited, progestin compatible); - Pregnancy spacing recommendation 18-24 mo; (4) **Cardiovascular risk** for women with pregnancy complications: - Preeclampsia, GDM, preterm birth, IUGR — all increase future CV risk; - Comprehensive CV risk assessment + lifestyle counseling; - Early ASCVD risk attention; (5) **Pelvic floor**: - **Pelvic floor physical therapy** — first-line for incontinence + prolapse + dyspareunia + pelvic pain — underutilized despite strong evidence; - Surgical options later if refractory; (6) **Return-to-activity counseling**: - Gradual exercise; - Sexual activity when ready (typically 4-6 wk if vaginal delivery uncomplicated); - Lifting, work return; (7) **Pediatric coordination**: well-baby care + maternal-infant dyad; (8) **Father / partner mental health**: paternal postpartum depression real — screen + treat; (9) **Future pregnancy planning**: interconception care; (10) **Postpartum-specific support**: groups, doulas, parenting classes; (11) **Multidisciplinary**: family medicine well-positioned + OB + pediatrics + behavioral health + lactation consultant + pelvic floor PT + nutrition + social work + family

---

Postpartum care: ''4th trimester'' ongoing not single visit (ACOG 2018). Comprehensive — mental health (PPD/anxiety), reproductive/contraception, lactation, physical recovery, chronic conditions (BP/DM as CV risk markers), pelvic floor PT. Father screening. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 32 ปี G2P2 — 6 wk postpartum visit; comprehensive postpartum care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Rapid IV correction in all"},{"label":"B","text":"Hyponatremia Workup + Management Primary Care"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore — Na 121 common"},{"label":"D","text":"Hold all medications without review"},{"label":"E","text":"Free water bolus for hyponatremia"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Hyponatremia Workup + Management Primary Care: (1) **Severity**: mild (Na 130-134), moderate (125-129), severe (< 125); symptoms guide urgency (confusion, seizure, coma); (2) **Volume status assessment** key: - **Hypovolemic** — diuretics, GI loss, third spacing, adrenal insufficiency; - **Euvolemic** (this patient) — **SIADH** most common cause (drugs — SSRI, carbamazepine, opioids, antipsychotics; lung — TB, pneumonia, small cell CA; CNS — stroke, infection, mass; surgery; postoperative; nausea; pain; idiopathic), hypothyroidism, adrenal insufficiency, primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute intake; - **Hypervolemic** — HF, cirrhosis, nephrotic syndrome, CKD; (3) **Workup**: - **Serum osmolality** (rule out pseudo / translocational): - Hypotonic (true hyponatremia, < 280): most cases; - Iso/hypertonic: hyperglycemia, mannitol, contrast, pseudohyponatremia (hypertriglyceridemia, paraproteinemia); - **Urine osmolality** (~ free water excretion ability): - Low (< 100) — primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute; - High (> 100) — ADH active — SIADH, hypovolemia, hypervolemia; - **Urine Na**: < 20 (hypovolemia, hypervolemia); > 40 (SIADH, diuretic, adrenal/thyroid); - **TSH + cortisol** (rule out treatable endocrine); - **BUN, Cr, glucose**; (4) **SIADH diagnosis**: euvolemic, hypotonic hyponatremia, urine osm > 100 (inappropriate concentration), urine Na > 30, normal kidney + adrenal + thyroid, no diuretic use; (5) **Treatment principles** — careful correction (RAPID correction → osmotic demyelination syndrome (ODS) — irreversible neuro damage, esp in chronic hyponatremia, malnutrition, hypokalemia, alcoholism, liver disease): - **Severe / symptomatic (seizure, coma) acute**: 3% saline 100 mL bolus IV may repeat; ICU; raise Na 4-6 mmol/L acutely; - **Maximum correction**: 8-10 mmol/L per 24 h, 18 mmol/L per 48 h (some say 6-8/24 h chronic, > 6 wk; lower in high-risk); - **Mild-moderate chronic asymptomatic**: address underlying cause; - **SIADH** treatment: - **Fluid restriction** (800-1200 mL/d) first-line; - **Salt + protein intake** (urea); - **Loop diuretic** + Na supplementation; - **Vaptans** (tolvaptan — V2 receptor antagonist) for refractory; cost + hepatotoxicity caution; - **Demeclocycline** alternative; - Discontinue offending drugs; (6) **Drug discontinuation review**: SSRIs, thiazides, NSAIDs, opioids, carbamazepine, antipsychotics, MDMA; (7) **Address underlying cause**: hypothyroid → replace; adrenal insufficiency → steroid; SIADH cause (infection, cancer, CNS); (8) **Outpatient follow-up close**: recheck Na in 24-48 h initial then weekly; (9) **Hospitalization** for severe / symptomatic / unable to correct outpatient / unstable; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + nephrology + endocrine if SIADH workup + ED if severe

---

Hyponatremia: volume + serum/urine osm + urine Na for diagnosis. SIADH common (drugs — SSRI; CNS; lung; postop). **Careful correction** to avoid ODS — max 8-10 mmol/L/24 h. Treat underlying + offending drugs. Severe → hypertonic saline ICU. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 70 ปี — Na 121, confused; chronic diuretic + SSRI; volume euvolemic by exam; urine Na 65, urine osm 380, serum osm 256';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No vaccinations immunocompromised"},{"label":"B","text":"Immunocompromised Primary Care + Immunology Basics"},{"label":"C","text":"Live vaccines no concern"},{"label":"D","text":"Ignore infection risks"},{"label":"E","text":"Standard schedule only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Immunocompromised Primary Care + Immunology Basics: (1) **Major types immunodeficiency**: - **Primary immunodeficiency** (PID) — genetic (CVID, X-linked agammaglobulinemia, severe combined ID, complement deficiencies, hyper-IgM, Wiskott-Aldrich, ataxia-telangiectasia, chronic granulomatous disease, etc.); often detected childhood; - **Secondary / acquired**: - **HIV**; - **Malignancy** (especially hematologic — lymphoma, leukemia, myeloma); - **Chemotherapy + targeted therapy** (CD20 — rituximab; BTK; checkpoint inhibitors); - **Immunosuppressants** (steroids, calcineurin inhibitors, MMF, azathioprine, methotrexate, biologics — TNF, IL-6, IL-17, IL-23, B-cell, T-cell, JAK inhibitors); - **Transplant** (solid organ + HSCT); - **Diabetes + uncontrolled hyperglycemia**; - **Splenectomy / asplenia (functional — sickle cell)**; - **Malnutrition**; - **CKD / ESRD**; - **Cirrhosis**; - **Aging (immunosenescence)**; - **Pregnancy** (mild physiologic immunosuppression); (2) **Workup suspected**: - Recurrent / unusual / severe infections; - Family history; - Quantitative immunoglobulins (IgG, IgA, IgM, IgE); - Lymphocyte subsets (CD3, CD4, CD8, CD19, CD56); - Vaccine response (T-cell-independent — Pneumovax; T-cell-dependent — tetanus); - Complement (CH50, C3, C4); - HIV; - Refer immunology specialist; (3) **Vaccinations in immunocompromised**: - **Generally AVOID live vaccines**: MMR, varicella, yellow fever, oral typhoid, BCG, oral polio, smallpox (limited situations); - **Recombinant Shingrix preferred** over live Zostavax in immunocompromised — ACIP recommends ≥ 19 yo immunocompromised; - **Inactivated vaccines safe but may have reduced response**: - **More doses or higher doses often** (e.g., 4 doses HepB 40 mcg dialysis); - Pneumococcal: PCV20 or PCV15 + PPSV23 8 wk apart (vs 1 yr) for immunocompromised; - **Vaccinate before immunosuppression when possible**: 2-4 wk live vaccines, 2 wk inactivated; - **HSCT recipients**: revaccination protocols (lose immune memory); - **Solid organ transplant**: optimize before transplant; live vaccines avoided lifelong after; - **Biologics specific**: - Anti-CD20 (rituximab) — vaccinate ≥ 4 wk before; reduced response × 6 mo after; - Anti-TNF — reduced response; reasonable to vaccinate while on; - Steroid: > 20 mg prednisone × 2 wk = immunosuppressed; (4) **Infection prevention + prophylaxis**: - **PCP (Pneumocystis jirovecii)** prophylaxis: TMP-SMX for HIV (CD4 < 200), post-transplant, certain chemo regimens, ANCA vasculitis, others; - **CMV prophylaxis**: post-transplant + selected; - **Fungal prophylaxis**: selected high-risk; - **Toxoplasmosis** for HIV (CD4 < 100); - **Hand hygiene + masking + avoidance** crowds + sick contacts; - **Food safety + water + travel precautions**; - **Pet safety** education (toxoplasmosis, salmonella); - **Wound care prompt**; - **Dental care** good hygiene; (5) **Recognition of infections**: - May present atypically (less fever, less inflammation); - Lower threshold for evaluation + treatment; - Broad differentials (opportunistic + community); - Cultures + biopsies; - Empiric treatment broader; (6) **Specific situations**: - **Asplenia**: vaccinate (encapsulated — pneumococcal, Hib, meningococcal ACWY + B), prophylactic antibiotic for some, medical alert ID, prompt evaluation fever + early empiric ceftriaxone; - **Sickle cell**: similar + penicillin prophylaxis childhood; - **Neutropenic fever**: emergency; - **HIV + low CD4**: opportunistic infection screening + prophylaxis; ART initiation; (7) **Cancer surveillance**: immunocompromised at increased risk for several cancers — screening per protocols + appropriate; (8) **Mental health + caregiver support**; (9) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + ID + immunology + transplant + oncology + relevant specialists + pharmacy + nursing + nutrition + behavioral health

---

Immunocompromised: types (primary + secondary). Workup if recurrent/unusual. Vaccines: **avoid live**, more doses, recombinant Shingrix preferred. Infection prevention + prophylaxis (PCP, CMV, etc.). Atypical presentations — low threshold. Asplenia considerations. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง immunology basics + immunocompromised primary care + vaccines + infections';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single nutrient focus"},{"label":"B","text":"Nutrition Science + Dietary Patterns Primary Care (AAFP + Dietary Guidelines 2020-2025)"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore dietary patterns"},{"label":"D","text":"Supplements for all"},{"label":"E","text":"Restrictive diet only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Nutrition Science + Dietary Patterns Primary Care (AAFP + Dietary Guidelines 2020-2025): (1) **Dietary Patterns Approach** (vs single nutrient) increasingly emphasized — DGA 2020-2025: - **Mediterranean** — strongest evidence CV, metabolic, cognitive, mortality (PREDIMED); plant-predominant, olive oil, fish, nuts, whole grains, moderate wine; - **DASH** — CV, BP (DASH-Sodium); similar to Mediterranean; - **Plant-based** — vegetarian / vegan / flexitarian; growing evidence; - **Healthy US-style** (DGA); - **Low-carb / Mediterranean-low-carb / ketogenic** — short-term weight + metabolic benefit; long-term data more limited; - **Intermittent fasting** — emerging; mixed evidence; - **Whole food, minimally processed** common theme — avoid ultra-processed (NOVA classification); (2) **Macronutrients** (DGA 2020-2025): - **Carbohydrate**: 45-65% — whole grains, fiber, complex; limit added sugar (< 10% calories); - **Protein**: 10-35% — plant + lean animal + fish; - **Fat**: 20-35% — unsaturated (mono + poly — olive, avocado, nuts, fish); limit saturated (< 10% calories — red meat, full-fat dairy, butter); avoid trans (essentially banned); - **Fiber**: 25-38 g/d (most Americans < 50%); - **Hydration**: ~ 2-3 L/d total; (3) **Specific nutrient considerations**: - **Sodium**: < 2300 mg/d (< 1500 high BP) — most Americans 3500+; - **Calcium + vit D**: bone + cancer protection; primarily food; supplements selective; - **Iron**: bioavailability heme > non-heme; pair with vit C; - **B12**: animal sources; supplement vegetarians + > 50 yo; - **Folate**: leafy green + fortified; pregnancy 400-800 mcg; - **Omega-3 (EPA + DHA)**: fatty fish 2x/wk; ALA plant sources lower conversion; supplements selected; - **Iodine**: salt fortified, seafood; - **Vit B-complex, antioxidants, magnesium, potassium, zinc** — food preferred; (4) **Special populations**: - **Pregnancy + lactation**: increased needs, folate, iron, DHA, calcium, vit D, choline; avoid alcohol, high mercury fish, raw, listeria-risk; - **Infants**: breast / formula + introduction solid 6 mo + iron-fortified + allergens early; - **Children + adolescents**: growth + development; calcium + vit D; limit added sugar / sugar-sweetened beverages; - **Older adults**: protein needs increase (1-1.2 g/kg); B12; vit D; calcium; address chewing + swallowing + appetite + social; - **Athletes**: macros + hydration + timing; - **Chronic disease specific**: - **DM**: carbohydrate management, glycemic index, Mediterranean / DASH; - **CKD**: protein moderate, K + phos as advances; - **CV**: Mediterranean + DASH; - **HF**: Na restriction + fluid; - **Cancer**: support during treatment; survivorship; - **Liver disease**: branched-chain amino acids, sodium; - **GI**: low-FODMAP for IBS, gluten-free celiac, low-residue acute IBD; (5) **Weight management**: - Modest calorie deficit; - Quality of diet > calories alone; - Behavioral + structured programs; - **Intermittent fasting** options; - **Very low calorie diets** for severe; - **Bariatric** for severe + comorbidity; (6) **Common myths + misconceptions**: - ''Dietary cholesterol'' less important than once thought (DGA 2015 removed limit); - ''Eat fat to lose fat'' qualified; - Detoxes + cleanses not evidence-based; - Supplements for healthy people limited benefit; - Sugar — not single villain but context; - **Ultra-processed food** epidemiologic concern; - **Food allergies vs intolerances** vs gluten sensitivity differ; (7) **Food insecurity** screening + intervention: critical SDOH; (8) **Food + medication interactions**: warfarin + vit K, MAOI + tyramine, grapefruit + meds; (9) **Cultural considerations** + personalization; (10) **Nutrition counseling**: brief in primary care; refer **dietitian / RDN** for comprehensive; Medicare benefit DM, CKD; (11) **Lifestyle medicine** integration; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + RDN/dietitian + diabetes educator + behavioral health + community programs + SDOH resources

---

Nutrition: dietary patterns > single nutrient. Mediterranean strongest evidence (PREDIMED). DASH, plant-based, healthy US-style. Macros + key nutrients. Special populations + chronic disease specific. Address food insecurity. RDN for comprehensive. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง nutrition science primary care + dietary patterns evidence';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No exercise needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Physical Activity Prescription + Exercise as Medicine (CDC + ACSM + DGA)"},{"label":"C","text":"Bed rest for chronic conditions"},{"label":"D","text":"Random advice only"},{"label":"E","text":"Single intensity prescribed"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Physical Activity Prescription + Exercise as Medicine (CDC + ACSM + DGA): (1) **Major impact**: physical activity = one of most impactful interventions for prevention + treatment of chronic disease, mental health, mortality; (2) **CDC + DGA 2018 Physical Activity Guidelines**: - **Adults**: - **150 min/wk moderate** (brisk walking) OR **75 min/wk vigorous** (jogging) OR combination; - **Plus muscle-strengthening ≥ 2 d/wk** (all major muscle groups); - More benefit with more — up to 300 min/wk; - Move more, sit less (sedentary behavior independent risk); - **Older adults**: above + balance training; modify per ability; - **Children + adolescents**: 60 min/d moderate-vigorous + muscle/bone strengthening 3x/wk; - **Pregnancy + postpartum**: 150 min/wk moderate; modify per stage; - **Chronic conditions**: still strongly recommended with adaptations; (3) **Exercise prescription components (FITT)**: - **F**requency; - **I**ntensity (talk test, HR zones, RPE); - **T**ime (duration); - **T**ype (aerobic, resistance, flexibility, balance); (4) **Intensity gauges**: - **Moderate**: increased HR + breathing + sweat; can talk but not sing; ~ 50-70% HRmax; - **Vigorous**: significantly increased; only few words; ~ 70-85% HRmax; - **Maximum HR**: 220 - age (rough); - **MET-min/wk** > 500 = adequate; (5) **Exercise as therapy** — specific evidence: - **Cardiovascular disease**: cardiac rehab, prevention, post-event; - **Hypertension**: 5-10 mmHg BP reduction; - **T2DM + prediabetes**: improved insulin sensitivity, A1c reduction; DPP includes; - **Dyslipidemia**: HDL + TG improvement; - **Obesity**: weight + body composition + maintenance; - **Cancer**: prevention multiple cancers, during/after treatment improvement (fatigue, QOL, recurrence reduction breast/colon); - **Mental health**: depression (effective as antidepressants for mild-moderate), anxiety, cognition, dementia prevention; - **Osteoporosis**: weight-bearing + resistance for bone; - **Osteoarthritis**: paradoxically beneficial — exercise = first-line; - **COPD**: pulmonary rehab; - **HF**: cardiac rehab + exercise training; - **PAD**: structured exercise > revascularization for claudication (CLEVER); - **Stroke recovery**: rehab + ongoing; - **Falls prevention**: tai chi, multimodal; - **Sleep**: improves; - **Mortality**: dose-response — even small amounts reduce; (6) **Pre-exercise screening**: ACSM updated — most healthy adults can begin without medical clearance; clearance for: known disease + symptoms + advanced age + intense activity; (7) **Specific populations**: - **Cardiac rehab** Class I post-MI, stable angina, HF, post-CABG/PCI/valve, PAD; - **Pulmonary rehab** for COPD + ILD + others; - **Cancer rehab** survivorship; - **Vestibular rehab**; - **Pelvic floor PT**; - **Vestibular** + **balance**; - **Children with disability**; (8) **Behavior change** principles (see separate): motivational interviewing, goal-setting, environmental, social, technology; (9) **Address barriers**: time, access, safety, weather, mobility, knowledge, motivation, cost, social; (10) **Technology**: wearables (Fitbit, Apple Watch, Garmin), apps, virtual programs, exergaming, gamification; (11) **Group + community programs**: SilverSneakers (Medicare), local gyms, parks + recreation, walking groups, faith-based; (12) **Provider counseling effective**: brief counseling + prescription + referral; Exercise is Medicine initiative; (13) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + exercise physiologist + PT + cardiac/pulm rehab + community programs + occupational therapy + behavioral health

---

Physical activity: 150 min/wk mod + strength 2x/wk adults (DGA). Less sedentary. FITT prescription. Therapy for nearly all chronic conditions (CV, DM, mental health, cancer, OA, etc.). Most adults can start without clearance. Cardiac/pulm rehab. Behavior change + tech + community. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง physical activity prescription + exercise as medicine';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No sleep history needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Sleep Medicine Basics + Primary Care (AASM)"},{"label":"C","text":"Pills for all sleep issues"},{"label":"D","text":"Ignore screen time"},{"label":"E","text":"Random recommendation"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Sleep Medicine Basics + Primary Care (AASM): (1) **Sleep architecture**: ~ 90 min cycles; NREM (N1, N2, N3 — deep) + REM (dreaming, memory consolidation); 4-6 cycles/night; (2) **Sleep duration recommendations (NSF + AAP)**: - Newborn 0-3 mo: 14-17 h; - Infant 4-11 mo: 12-15 h; - Toddler 1-2 yr: 11-14 h; - Preschool 3-5 yr: 10-13 h; - School age 6-13 yr: 9-11 h; - Teen 14-17 yr: 8-10 h (often inadequate — early school start times, screens); - Adult 18-64: 7-9 h; - Older adult ≥ 65: 7-8 h; (3) **Sleep deprivation effects**: - Acute: cognition, mood, immune, metabolic; - Chronic (< 7 h adult): increased mortality, CV disease, DM, obesity, mental health, accidents (drowsy driving = drunk driving), cancer (shift work IARC group 2A); (4) **Sleep hygiene** — foundation: - Regular schedule (even weekends); - Dark, cool, quiet bedroom (60-67°F); - Bed for sleep + sex only; - Avoid screens 1+ h before bed (blue light); - Caffeine cutoff afternoon; - Alcohol disrupts; - Exercise (not late); - Limit naps (< 30 min, early); - Sunlight exposure morning; - Relaxation routine; - Manage stress; (5) **Major sleep disorders primary care**: - **Insomnia disorder** — see separate (CBT-I first-line); - **OSA** — see separate (CPAP + lifestyle + GLP-1 emerging); - **Central sleep apnea** — HF, opioid, idiopathic; - **Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS) / Willis-Ekbom**: urge to move + dysesthesia + evening + relief with movement; Workup: ferritin (target > 75-100, supplement), Cr, glucose, thyroid; Treatment: iron repletion if low; alpha-2-delta ligands (gabapentin, pregabalin — first-line shift); dopamine agonists (pramipexole, ropinirole — augmentation issue, less preferred now); rotigotine patch; opioids low-dose refractory; - **Narcolepsy**: excessive daytime sleepiness + cataplexy (type 1) + sleep paralysis + hypnagogic hallucinations; polysomnography + MSLT; modafinil/armodafinil, sodium oxybate, pitolisant, solriamfetol; refer sleep medicine; - **Circadian rhythm disorders**: delayed/advanced sleep phase, shift work, jet lag, irregular; melatonin + light therapy + chronotherapy; - **Parasomnias**: sleepwalking, night terrors, REM behavior disorder (alpha-synucleinopathy risk — Parkinson, DLB, MSA progression); - **Hypersomnia disorders**: idiopathic, Kleine-Levin; - **Bruxism**: dental + stress; - **Sleep-related movement disorders**: PLMS; (6) **Pediatric sleep**: - Sleep training (multiple methods debated); - SIDS prevention (back to sleep, firm surface, no co-sleeping same bed, no soft objects); - OSA in children — adenotonsillectomy first-line; - ADHD + sleep bidirectional; - Adolescent later chronotype + school start times advocacy; (7) **Pregnancy + postpartum**: sleep changes; RLS common; OSA can develop; preeclampsia association; (8) **Mental health bidirectional**: depression, anxiety, PTSD, bipolar — sleep disruption + treatment; (9) **Substance use + sleep**: stimulants, alcohol, opioids, marijuana — affect sleep; (10) **Sleep + cognitive aging**: deep sleep + glymphatic clearance + dementia prevention emerging evidence; (11) **Drowsy driving + occupational** safety; commercial drivers OSA screening; (12) **Sleep tracking technology**: wearables increasingly accurate; orthosomnia (anxiety from data); (13) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + sleep medicine + ENT (OSA pediatric) + dental sleep (oral appliance) + behavioral health (CBT-I) + neurology + cardiology

---

Sleep: 7-9 h adult; sleep hygiene foundation. Major disorders — insomnia (CBT-I), OSA (CPAP), RLS (iron + gabapentinoid), narcolepsy (sleep med referral), parasomnias. Pediatric considerations. Pregnancy + mental health bidirectional. Drowsy driving + tech. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง sleep medicine basics + sleep disorders primary care + sleep as health';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No screening needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Pediatric Development + Screening Primary Care (AAP Bright Futures)"},{"label":"C","text":"Wait and see for all delays"},{"label":"D","text":"Adult assessment for children"},{"label":"E","text":"Single milestone check"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Pediatric Development + Screening Primary Care (AAP Bright Futures): (1) **Developmental domains**: - **Motor** (gross + fine); - **Language** (receptive + expressive); - **Cognitive**; - **Social-emotional**; - **Adaptive / self-help**; (2) **Surveillance vs screening**: - **Surveillance**: ongoing process at every visit — history, parent concerns, observation; - **Screening**: standardized tool at specific intervals; (3) **Recommended screening intervals (AAP)**: - **General developmental** (ASQ, PEDS): 9, 18, 30 mo; - **Autism-specific** (M-CHAT-R/F): 18 + 24 mo; - **Maternal depression**: 1, 2, 4, 6 mo; - **Lead**: targeted; many recommend universal Medicaid; - **Anemia**: 9-12 mo; - **TB**: targeted; - **Lipid**: 9-11 + 17-21 yo; - **HIV**: 13+ yo; - **Behavioral**: at all WCV (PSC, CBCL); - **Adolescent depression** (PHQ-A): annually 12+ yo; (4) **Key milestones (AAP 2022 updated)**: - **2 mo**: social smile, coo, lift head prone; - **4 mo**: laugh, roll, reach; - **6 mo**: sit support, babble, transfer; - **9 mo**: pincer grasp, mama/dada, wave bye, separation anxiety; - **12 mo**: walk, 1-2 words, pat-a-cake; - **15 mo**: 3-5 words, point to wants; - **18 mo**: 10+ words, 1-step commands, run, scribble, parallel play; - **24 mo**: 2-word phrases, run + kick ball, points to body parts; - **3 yr**: 3-word sentences, draw circle, tricycle, dress with help; - **4 yr**: count to 10, draw person, hop, dress self; - **5 yr**: print name, skip, count to 20, friend relationships; (5) **Red flags requiring evaluation**: - **No social smile by 3 mo**; - **Cannot hold head up by 4 mo**; - **No babbling by 9 mo**; - **No words by 16 mo**; - **No 2-word phrases by 24 mo**; - **Loss of skills any age** (regression); - **Lack of social interest / engagement**; - **No pointing by 18 mo**; - **No interactive play**; - **Hand preference < 18 mo** (could indicate hemiparesis); (6) **Common conditions screening detects**: - **Autism spectrum disorder** (1 in 36 — CDC); - **Speech-language delay**; - **Intellectual disability**; - **ADHD** (older); - **Learning disability**; - **Hearing loss**; - **Vision impairment**; - **Cerebral palsy** + motor disorders; (7) **Early intervention referral don''t delay**: - **Part C (IDEA — birth to 3)** — Early Intervention free; - **Part B (IDEA — 3-21)** — school-based services; IEP; 504 plan; - Concurrent referrals — audiology, vision, specialty; - Family training + support; (8) **Vision + hearing**: - Newborn hearing screen mandatory most states; - Vision screening at WCV per AAP + AAO; - Photoscreener instrument-based 3+ yo; - Refer ophthalmology if positive or risk; (9) **Other screening**: - Newborn metabolic + endocrine screening (state panels); - CCHD screening newborn (critical congenital heart); - Hip dysplasia (Barlow + Ortolani + Galeazzi infancy); - Scoliosis adolescent; (10) **Family-centered communication**: parents are partners; reassure normalcy + concerning findings; cultural humility; (11) **Special situations**: prematurity (corrected age), adoption, foster, history of risk; (12) **Anticipatory guidance** at each visit per Bright Futures; (13) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + EI team + audiology + ophthalmology + speech-language + OT + PT + developmental pediatrics + autism specialist + school + family

---

Pediatric development: surveillance every visit + screening (ASQ 9/18/30 mo, M-CHAT-R/F 18+24 mo). Key milestones knowledge. Red flags → don''t delay EI referral. Audiology + vision + other screens. Family-centered. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
