update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Random medication choice"},{"label":"B","text":"Medications in Pregnancy + Lactation (FDA PLLR + LactMed + ACOG)"},{"label":"C","text":"Stop all medications pregnancy"},{"label":"D","text":"Adult dosing only"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore lactation considerations"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Medications in Pregnancy + Lactation (FDA PLLR + LactMed + ACOG): (1) **FDA Pregnancy + Lactation Labeling Rule (PLLR)** — 2015 replaced old A/B/C/D/X categories: - **Pregnancy summary** with risk; - **Lactation summary**; - **Females + males of reproductive potential**; - More nuanced + evidence-based; categories abandoned; (2) **Key principles**: - **No medication completely safe** in pregnancy/lactation; - **No medication automatically contraindicated** — assess benefit vs risk to mother + fetus/infant; - **Untreated condition often greater risk** than medication (e.g., depression, asthma, epilepsy, HIV); - **Trimester matters**: 1st (organogenesis 2-8 wk PCD), 2nd, 3rd, near delivery, postpartum; - **Lowest effective dose + duration**; - **Preferred agents within class** when alternatives; - **Counsel + document shared decision**; - **Resources**: LactMed (free NIH), TERIS, Reprotox, MotherToBaby, ACOG/specialty guidelines; (3) **Common medications + pregnancy**: - **Antibiotics**: penicillins / cephalosporins / azithromycin generally safe; AVOID — tetracyclines (after 1st trimester — bones + teeth), fluoroquinolones (cartilage, FDA caution though emerging more nuanced), aminoglycosides (ototoxic), TMP-SMX (1st trim — folate antagonist; 3rd trim — kernicterus, neonatal hyperbilirubinemia); nitrofurantoin avoid 38+ wk (hemolytic anemia neonatal G6PD); - **Hypertension**: methyldopa, labetalol, nifedipine OK; AVOID — ACE/ARB (renal + skull anomalies 2nd-3rd trim), atenolol (IUGR); - **DM**: insulin preferred; metformin (acceptable per ACOG); glyburide (decreased use — neonatal hypoglycemia); - **Anticoagulation**: heparin / LMWH preferred (no placental transfer); warfarin teratogen (esp 1st trim); DOACs limited data, avoid; - **Anti-seizure**: minimize teratogens; preferred — lamotrigine, levetiracetam; AVOID — valproic acid (highest teratogenicity NTD + cognitive); carbamazepine, phenytoin moderate; supplement folate 4 mg before + during pregnancy; - **Antidepressants**: SSRIs generally acceptable (sertraline preferred), paroxetine slight CV concern 1st trim (older data), avoid abrupt discontinuation; benefits often outweigh risks for moderate-severe depression; - **NSAIDs**: avoid 3rd trim (premature closure ductus arteriosus, oligohydramnios, kidney); 1st-2nd trim limited use OK; - **Acetaminophen**: generally safe but recent observational concerns ADHD/autism (causality not established); minimize unnecessary use; - **Opioids**: pregnancy MOUD (buprenorphine, methadone) for OUD better than detox; otherwise minimize; neonatal abstinence; - **Vaccines**: inactivated safe + recommended (Tdap, flu, COVID, RSV); avoid live (MMR, varicella, yellow fever — postpone if possible); - **Imaging**: minimize radiation, US + MRI safer; CT with shielding selected; iodinated contrast generally avoid; gadolinium avoid (especially 1st trim); - **Anesthesia**: regional preferred when possible; (4) **Common medications + lactation**: - **LactMed first-resource**; - **Generally safe**: most antibiotics, common antihypertensives, SSRIs (sertraline, paroxetine — minimal milk transfer), low-dose opioids brief, insulin, levothyroxine, hydroxychloroquine, low-dose steroids; - **Caution**: pseudoephedrine (↓ milk supply), bromocriptine/cabergoline (suppress lactation), lithium (high transfer, monitor infant), warfarin OK; - **Avoid**: chemotherapy, radioactive iodine, ergot alkaloids; (5) **Periconception counseling**: - Folate 400 mcg routine, 4 mg if prior NTD or AED use; - Review chronic medications + optimize teratogenic; - DM, BP, thyroid optimization; - Vaccinations update; - Lifestyle (smoking, alcohol, substance, weight, nutrition); - Genetic carrier screening; (6) **Special populations**: - **OUD pregnancy**: MOUD preferred; - **HIV**: ART continued / initiated; - **Epilepsy**: minimize teratogens; - **Mental illness**: weigh untreated vs treatment risks; - **Autoimmune**: hydroxychloroquine OK; some biologics; - **Chronic pain**: minimize opioids; - **Transplant**: immunosuppression continued; (7) **Postpartum + lactation drug choices**: minimize unnecessary; choose preferred; LactMed look-up; (8) **Father-to-be exposures + paternal effects**: emerging consideration; (9) **Documentation**: shared decisions, counseling, alternatives considered; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + OB + MFM + pharmacy + specialty (psych, ID, etc.) + neonatology + lactation

---

Pregnancy + lactation pharm: PLLR (categories abandoned). Benefit-risk individualized. Untreated condition often worse. LactMed + resources. Common safe/avoid lists per condition. Periconception optimization. Special populations. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง pharmacology in pregnancy + lactation + clinical decision-making';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Treatment-focused only"},{"label":"B","text":"Preventive Medicine Principles (USPSTF + CDC + Healthy People 2030)"},{"label":"C","text":"No screening — wait for symptoms"},{"label":"D","text":"Single intervention"},{"label":"E","text":"Maximum testing always"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Preventive Medicine Principles (USPSTF + CDC + Healthy People 2030): (1) **Levels of prevention**: - **Primary** — prevent disease occurrence (vaccination, lifestyle modification, smoking cessation, fluoride, seatbelts); - **Secondary** — early detection + treatment (screening — cancer, BP, glucose); - **Tertiary** — limit complications of existing disease (cardiac rehab, glycemic control to prevent complications); - **Quaternary** — protect from harms of medicine itself (avoid overtesting, overtreatment, overdiagnosis); (2) **USPSTF grades**: - **A** strong recommendation high certainty net benefit; - **B** moderate certainty; - **C** small net benefit — individual decision; - **D** recommend against; - **I** insufficient evidence; - A + B routinely cover preventive services under ACA without cost-sharing; (3) **Key USPSTF preventive recommendations adults**: - **BP screening** all adults ≥ 18; - **Cholesterol screening** age-based; - **DM screening** 35-70 + overweight; - **Cancer screening**: - Cervical 21-65; - Breast 40-74 biennial (USPSTF 2024 lowered to 40); - Colorectal 45-75 (lowered from 50); - Lung 50-80 with 20 pack-year history; - Prostate 55-69 shared decision; - Cervical, skin (selected), oral; - **Osteoporosis** women 65+ (younger if risk); - **AAA** men 65-75 ever-smoker; - **Hepatitis C** all adults 18-79; - **Hepatitis B** all adults (2023); - **HIV** 15-65; - **Latent TB** at-risk; - **STIs** risk-based; - **Depression** all adults including pregnant + postpartum; - **Anxiety** adults < 65 (USPSTF 2023); - **Substance use** alcohol + drugs + tobacco; - **IPV** women reproductive age; - **Falls** ≥ 65; - **Lifestyle counseling** weight, exercise, diet, smoking; (4) **Vaccinations** per CDC schedule (see separate); (5) **Choosing Wisely / Quaternary prevention**: avoid: - Unnecessary cancer screening (older, low risk, less benefit); - Routine imaging headache, LBP; - Routine EKG/CXR asymptomatic; - Annual physical detailed labs not evidence-based; - Antibiotic for viral; - PPI long-term without indication; - Polypharmacy without rationale; - Cancer screening with limited life expectancy; (6) **Shared decision-making essential** for many — especially C-grade or where benefits/harms close; (7) **Risk assessment + stratification**: Pooled Cohort Equations, FRAX, Tyrer-Cuzick, Lung CA risk, etc.; (8) **Counseling effective in primary care** — even brief (e.g., smoking cessation 5 As, alcohol SBIRT); (9) **Population health + community level**: water fluoridation, immunization programs, tobacco policy, food labeling, built environment, school health, workplace wellness; (10) **Health equity in prevention**: stratify outcomes + address disparities; (11) **Healthy People 2030 framework**: leading health indicators across domains; (12) **Implementation in practice**: EHR reminders, team-based delivery, registries, outreach; (13) **Pediatric preventive** (Bright Futures): - Vaccines per CDC; - Growth + development; - Lead, lipid, anemia, dental, vision/hearing screening; - Anticipatory guidance; (14) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + nursing + APP + behavioral health + dietitian + public health + community + school + workplace + family

---

Prevention: 4 levels (primary, secondary, tertiary, quaternary — avoid overuse). USPSTF grades guide preventive services. Key recommendations adults. Counseling effective. Risk stratification. Community + policy levels. Equity. Implementation in practice. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง preventive medicine principles + USPSTF + levels of prevention';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Blame individual physician"},{"label":"B","text":"Patient Safety + Just Culture (IHI + AHRQ + IOM)"},{"label":"C","text":"Hide errors"},{"label":"D","text":"No reporting system"},{"label":"E","text":"Single error = single fix"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Patient Safety + Just Culture (IHI + AHRQ + IOM): (1) **Magnitude**: medical errors ~ 3rd leading cause of death US (Makary BMJ 2016 estimate ~ 250,000/yr); primary care + ambulatory errors common but less studied; (2) **IOM (now NAM) framework** — ''**To Err is Human**'' (1999) + ''Crossing the Quality Chasm'' (2001): - System problem, not individual; - Build safer systems; - 6 aims: Safe + Effective + Patient-centered + Timely + Efficient + Equitable; - ''Quintuple Aim'' adds clinician well-being + equity; (3) **Just culture**: - Distinguish: - **Human error** (slip, lapse) → console + system fix; - **At-risk behavior** (taking shortcut) → coach; - **Reckless behavior** (knowing risk) → discipline; - **Psychological safety** — speak up about safety without fear; - **Learning culture** > blame culture; - Reduces underreporting + improves system improvement; (4) **High-Reliability Organization (HRO) principles** (Weick + Sutcliffe): - Preoccupation with failure; - Reluctance to simplify; - Sensitivity to operations; - Commitment to resilience; - Deference to expertise; (5) **Common error categories primary care**: - **Diagnostic errors** — missed, delayed, wrong (especially cancer, MI, stroke, infection, PE) — leading cause primary care malpractice; - **Medication errors** — prescribing, dispensing, monitoring, communication; - **Communication failures**: handoffs, results, between team; - **Care coordination + referrals**: lost referrals, missed results; - **Test result management**: missed abnormal results most common; - **Documentation**: unclear, illegible (less now), missing; - **Follow-up failures**; - **Care transitions**: hospital-to-home, between settings; (6) **System solutions**: - **Closed-loop communication**: results → patient → action → documentation; - **Robust safety net systems**: EHR reminders, automated follow-up, recall systems, panel management; - **Standardization + checklists**: surgical safety, central line, OB, sepsis, NEW for primary care; - **Decision support**: EHR alerts, clinical pathways, decision aids; - **Medication safety**: e-prescribing, drug interaction checking, medication reconciliation, double-checks for high-risk; - **Read-back + verification**; - **Adequate staffing + workload**; - **Fatigue + burnout reduction**; (7) **Reporting + analysis**: - **Voluntary incident reporting** (low-threshold, blame-free) + system feedback; - **Root cause analysis (RCA)** for serious events — identify system causes; - **Failure modes + effects analysis (FMEA)** prospective risk identification; - **Mortality + morbidity conferences** — learning oriented; - **AHRQ Common Formats** standardized; (8) **Disclosure of errors**: - Ethical + legal (most jurisdictions); - **CANDOR program** — Communication and Optimal Resolution; - Empathic, honest, system focus; - Reduces litigation when done well; - Apology laws (varies); (9) **Patient engagement in safety**: - Speak up programs; - Medication reconciliation involvement; - Question + understand care; - Patient + family advisory councils; (10) **Health literacy + plain language** essential; (11) **Specific safety priorities** WHO, AHRQ, Joint Commission goals: - Patient ID; - Communication of test results / handoffs; - Medication safety (high-alert); - Infection prevention; - Falls; - Surgical safety; - Suicide prevention; - DVT prophylaxis; - Sepsis recognition; (12) **Outpatient-specific safety**: telephone advice protocols, after-hours coverage, cross-coverage, test results management, abnormal result tracking, no-show follow-up, controlled substances; (13) **Clinician well-being + safety**: 2nd victim phenomenon (clinician trauma after adverse event); peer support, debriefing; (14) **Resources**: IHI, AHRQ PSNet, Joint Commission, state QIOs, NPSF (now part of IHI); (15) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + risk + quality + patients + administration + IT + nursing + pharmacy + legal + insurance

---

Patient safety: system focus (IOM). Just culture (distinguish human error, at-risk, reckless). HRO principles. Common errors (diagnostic, medication, communication, results). System solutions (closed-loop, checklists, decision support). CANDOR disclosure. Patient engagement. Wellbeing — 2nd victim. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง patient safety + medical errors + just culture in primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Random referrals"},{"label":"B","text":"Specialty Referral Management Optimization"},{"label":"C","text":"No follow-up"},{"label":"D","text":"Fax-only communication"},{"label":"E","text":"Specialist makes all decisions"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Specialty Referral Management Optimization: (1) **Referral problems**: long wait times, inadequate information transfer (both directions), missed referrals, duplicated tests, lack of feedback, fragmented care, patient confusion; (2) **Structured referral processes**: - **Standardized templates** with key clinical info; - **Triage at receiving end** to prioritize urgency; - **Referral coordinators / hubs**; - **Two-way communication** mandated; - **Closing the loop**: receipt confirmation, consult report back; (3) **eConsults / asynchronous specialty consultation**: - PCP submits structured question + relevant data; - Specialist responds within days; - Avoids in-person visit ~ 50%+ for appropriate conditions; - Project ECHO model — telementoring + capacity building (Sanjeev Arora UNM); evidence in multiple conditions (HCV, chronic pain, opioid use); - Improves access esp underserved; (4) **Co-management + collaborative care**: - **Collaborative Care Model** (mental health) — measurement-based + care manager + specialist consultation; - **Cardio-renal-endocrine** coordination; - **Specialty-PCP shared chronic disease management** (e.g., cardiology shared care HF, endocrine shared DM); (5) **Direct booking + scheduling tools**: - Patient self-scheduling specialists with PCP referral approval; - Shared calendars; - Reduce gatekeeper burden; (6) **Network optimization**: - **Narrow networks** with quality + cost focus; - **Centers of excellence** for complex; - **Direct contracting**; (7) **Information exchange**: - **EHR same system** (Epic, Cerner) — facilitates; - **HIEs (Health Information Exchanges)** across systems; - **FHIR + interoperability** standards; - **Structured + complete referral data + consult notes**; (8) **Quality metrics**: - **Time to specialist appointment**; - **Information transfer completeness** both directions; - **Follow-up completion**; - **Patient experience** with referral process; - **Avoidable specialty visits** (could have been handled in primary care with support); (9) **Patient experience improvements**: - **Transparent process** + expectations; - **Pre-referral education**; - **Logistics support** (transportation, scheduling, navigation); - **Post-referral follow-up**; (10) **Capacity building primary care**: - **Specialist mentoring** (ECHO model); - **Continuing education**; - **Clinical decision support**; - **In-clinic specialty support** (visiting specialist, mini-residencies); - **Practice transformation**; - More primary care can manage = less referral needed; (11) **Specific high-volume referral pathways**: - Cardiology, GI, dermatology, orthopedics, psychiatry — most common; - Standardized pathways; - Pre-referral workup expectations; (12) **Equity in specialty access**: - Insurance + cost barriers; - Geographic / transportation; - Language access; - Cultural fit; - **Closing referral gap** for underserved; (13) **Workforce considerations**: - Specialty + primary care workforce alignment; - Mid-level provider integration; - Telemedicine expansion; (14) **Cost considerations**: - Avoid unnecessary specialty visits + duplicative testing; - Specialty cost + value variation; (15) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + specialists + care coordinators + referral coordinators + IT + administration + quality + patients + insurance + community partners

---

Specialty referral: structured + close the loop. eConsults + ECHO + co-management. Direct booking. Information exchange. Quality metrics. Patient experience. Capacity building primary care. Equity. Workforce. Cost. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — improve specialty referral process + reduce wait times + improve information transfer';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"In-person only"},{"label":"B","text":"Telemedicine in Primary Care — Best Practices (ATA + AAFP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Random telemedicine use"},{"label":"D","text":"Skip privacy considerations"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid technology"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Telemedicine in Primary Care — Best Practices (ATA + AAFP): (1) **Modalities**: - **Synchronous video**: real-time, most like in-person; - **Synchronous audio**: telephone only; - **Asynchronous (store + forward)**: patient submits photo/info; - **Remote patient monitoring (RPM)**: BP, glucose, weight, SpO2, ECG, wearables; - **eVisits**: messaging-based; - **eConsults**: provider-to-provider (see separate); (2) **Appropriate use cases**: - Routine chronic disease follow-up (HTN, DM, lipid); - Behavioral health (depression, anxiety, substance use, therapy); - Medication management + refills; - Minor acute conditions (URI, skin rashes, UTI selected); - Follow-up after labs/imaging; - Lifestyle counseling; - Care management + coordination; - Pre + post-procedural; - Specialty consultations; - Post-acute / hospital follow-up; - Rural + access-limited; (3) **Not appropriate**: - Acute serious conditions needing physical exam; - Procedures; - Imaging-required diagnoses; - When physical exam essential; - Some sensitive issues (preferences vary); - Technology / language barriers severe; (4) **Best practices visit conduct**: - **Pre-visit**: technology check, privacy/HIPAA, intake forms, consent; - **Setting**: quiet, well-lit, eye-level camera, professional appearance; - **Introduction**: identify self + confirm patient identity + setting privacy + explain technology; - **Webside manner**: eye contact (look at camera), unhurried, attentive, address technology issues; - **Limited physical exam adapted**: visual inspection, patient-performed maneuvers (palpation, ROM), home BP/wt/temp, smartphone tools; - **Documentation**: telemedicine modality + duration + key findings; - **Follow-up + close the loop**; (5) **Technology considerations**: - **Platforms**: Epic MyChart Video, Doxy.me, Zoom for Healthcare, others; HIPAA-compliant; - **Patient access**: smartphone, tablet, computer; broadband; - **Alternatives** for digital divide: telephone, in-person; - **Backup plan** for technical issues; - **Patient portal integration**; (6) **Regulatory + reimbursement**: - **Post-PHE COVID landscape evolving** — pre-PHE many restrictions removed; - **Audio-only** parity in many states (varies); - **Interstate licensure** — Interstate Medical Licensure Compact + state-specific telehealth licensure; - **Controlled substance prescribing** — DEA rules evolving post-PHE (Ryan Haight Act + extensions); - **Reimbursement parity** — Medicare + Medicaid + commercial; varies; - **Originating site** restrictions historically (many waived); (7) **Quality + safety considerations**: - **Safe vs in-person?** — emerging evidence comparable many conditions; - **Triage carefully** — when to convert to in-person; - **Care transitions to in-person** when needed; - **No-show + access disparities**; - **Outcomes monitoring**; (8) **Health equity**: - **Digital divide** — broadband, devices, digital literacy, language; - **Provide alternatives** (audio, community-based, in-person); - **Support resources**: community Wi-Fi, lending programs, low-cost broadband (FCC ACP); (9) **Special populations**: - **Pediatric**: parent involvement; specific considerations (developmental, parental support); - **Geriatric**: technology support; in-home help; - **Mental health**: very effective + accessible; specific platforms; - **Underserved + rural**: significant benefit + access; - **Disabilities**: accessibility (captions, sign language interpreter); - **Limited English**: video interpreters; (10) **Practice integration**: - **Workflow design**: scheduling, intake, visit, follow-up, billing; - **Hybrid practice**: balance + flexibility; - **Staff training**; - **Patient education + materials**; - **Quality improvement** ongoing; (11) **Provider considerations**: - **Burnout**: differing dynamics; - **Schedule flexibility** opportunity; - **Skills development**: webside manner, virtual exam, technology proficiency; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + IT + nursing + scheduling + billing + administration + patients + community + advocacy

---

Telemedicine: modalities + appropriate use cases. Best practices (pre-visit, setting, webside manner, virtual exam, documentation). Technology + regulatory + reimbursement evolving. Quality + safety + equity. Special populations. Practice integration. Provider considerations. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — telemedicine workflow integration + best practices';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No preparedness needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Disaster + Emergency Preparedness Primary Care (ASPR + CDC + AAFP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single plan covers all"},{"label":"D","text":"Ignore vulnerable populations"},{"label":"E","text":"Wait until disaster occurs"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Disaster + Emergency Preparedness Primary Care (ASPR + CDC + AAFP): (1) **Types disasters/emergencies**: - **Natural**: hurricanes, floods, earthquakes, wildfires, tornadoes, blizzards, extreme heat/cold, drought; - **Public health**: pandemics (COVID-19), endemic outbreaks (measles, foodborne), bioterrorism; - **Technological**: power outages, cyber attacks, water contamination, transportation accidents, chemical/radiation; - **Mass casualty**: shootings, terrorism; - **Combined**: refugee crises, war; (2) **Phases of disaster cycle**: - **Mitigation** (reduce risk); - **Preparedness** (planning); - **Response** (acute); - **Recovery** (long-term); (3) **Primary care role**: - **Continuity of care**: maintain access for patients during/after; medication refills, chronic disease management; - **Surge capacity**: handle increased volume during outbreaks; - **Triage + screening**; - **Vaccination delivery**: outbreak + routine; - **Mental health support**: acute trauma + chronic; - **Communications**: with patients, public health, hospital; - **Vulnerable populations**: medically dependent, oxygen, dialysis, mental health, homeless, immigrants, elderly, disabled, low-income; (4) **Practice preparedness plan elements**: - **All-hazards approach**: flexible framework; - **Staff training + drills**; - **Communication plan**: internal staff, patient outreach (text, social, website), referral partners, public health, suppliers; - **Continuity of operations (COOP)**: alternate site, remote work, paper backup, key personnel; - **EHR + data backup + cybersecurity**; - **Supply chain**: medications, vaccines, PPE, basic supplies; - **Power + utilities** backup planning; - **Medication continuity** for patients (e.g., chronic medications stockpile, refill protocols, mail order, partnerships); - **Mutual aid agreements**; - **Patient outreach for chronic conditions** (HF, COPD, DM, dialysis, oxygen-dependent); - **Mental health response**; - **Public health collaboration**; (5) **Pandemic-specific (COVID lessons)**: - **Telemedicine** rapid implementation; - **Outpatient testing + triage**; - **Infection prevention + PPE**; - **Vaccination delivery** mass + accessible; - **Long COVID** management; - **Health equity** — disparities amplified; - **Workforce wellness** + burnout; - **Misinformation counter**; (6) **Climate change health impacts**: - **Heat-related illness** + heat waves; - **Vector-borne expansion** (Lyme, dengue, etc.); - **Air quality** (wildfire smoke, ozone, particulate); - **Allergies** worsening; - **Mental health** (climate anxiety, displacement); - **Water + food security**; - **Migration + conflict**; - Address adaptation + advocacy; (7) **Bioterrorism awareness**: - Recognize unusual presentations (anthrax, plague, smallpox, tularemia, botulism, viral hemorrhagic); - Report immediately to public health; - Personal protection; (8) **Mass casualty preparation**: - Active shooter / Stop the Bleed training; - Triage + first aid; - Mental health support; (9) **Recovery + long-term**: - Continued mental health (PTSD); - Chronic disease decompensation; - Health system rebuilding; - Equity considerations; (10) **National framework**: - **ESF #8** (Health + Medical) under Stafford Act; - **National Response Framework**; - **HHS ASPR** (Administration for Strategic Preparedness + Response); - **State + local public health** departments; - **HPP** (Hospital Preparedness Program); - **PHEP** (Public Health Emergency Preparedness); (11) **Resources**: ASPR TRACIE, CDC Emergency Preparedness, AAFP Disaster Resources, Healthcare Coalitions; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + emergency management + public health + hospital + EMS + community partners + government + faith + business + nonprofits

---

Disaster preparedness: all-hazards approach. Practice plan (staff, communication, COOP, supply chain, vulnerable patients). Pandemic lessons (telemedicine, equity). Climate change. Bioterrorism. Mass casualty. Recovery long-term. National framework + resources. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — disaster preparedness + emergency response planning for primary care practice';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No accreditation needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Practice Accreditation + Recognition (NCQA + Joint Commission + URAC)"},{"label":"C","text":"Random pursuit"},{"label":"D","text":"Cost prohibitive — avoid"},{"label":"E","text":"Single audit only"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Practice Accreditation + Recognition (NCQA + Joint Commission + URAC): (1) **PCMH (Patient-Centered Medical Home)** — most common: - **NCQA PCMH** — 3 levels of recognition; comprehensive criteria across team-based care, population health, care management, behavioral health integration, care coordination, patient engagement, performance measurement; - Demonstrates practice transformation; - Sometimes incentive payments; - Renewal triennial; - Continuous improvement focus; (2) **Joint Commission Ambulatory Care Accreditation** — broader healthcare accreditation; (3) **URAC Patient-Centered Health Care Home** — alternative; (4) **HRSA Health Center Program** (FQHCs) — federal funding + requirements; (5) **Specialty / condition-specific recognitions**: - **Diabetes Recognition Program** (NCQA DRP); - **Heart/Stroke Recognition Program**; - **Behavioral Health Integration**; - **Patient-Centered Specialty Practice** (NCQA PCSP); (6) **Hospital + system accreditation**: Joint Commission, DNV, HFAP; (7) **Recognition vs accreditation**: - Recognition often focused on specific model (PCMH); - Accreditation broader quality + safety; - Both demonstrate commitment + earn benefits; (8) **Value beyond compliance**: - Practice transformation; - Quality improvement focus; - Team-based care development; - Population health capabilities; - Performance measurement; - Continuous learning; - Staff + patient engagement; - Some payer incentives + alignment with value-based; (9) **Process for PCMH (NCQA)**: - Practice readiness assessment; - Application + documentation submission; - Self-evaluation against criteria; - Site visit or virtual review; - Recognition decision + level; - Annual reporting + improvement; - Renewal triennial; (10) **Costs + resources**: - Application fees; - Internal resources (staff time, project management); - Practice transformation investment; - Often supported by ACOs, payers, state programs; (11) **Critiques + considerations**: - Documentation burden; - Cost; - Variable evidence on outcomes (some positive, some neutral); - Real practice change vs paperwork; - Continuous improvement integration; (12) **Other quality programs**: - **CMS recognitions**: PCMH, ACO certification, MIPS APMs; - **State + regional programs**; - **Health plan recognition**: many private insurers; (13) **Maintenance of Certification (MOC)** for physicians — ABFM, ABIM, others — distinct from practice accreditation; (14) **DEI + equity certifications** emerging: equity-focused accreditation supplements; (15) **Multidisciplinary effort**: leadership + clinicians + administration + quality + IT + nursing + behavioral health + patients + consultants

---

Practice accreditation: NCQA PCMH most common + Joint Commission + URAC. Promotes practice transformation, team-based care, population health, performance measurement. Recognition vs accreditation. Process + costs. Critiques. CMS + state alignment with value-based. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — primary care practice accreditation + certification + recognition programs';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Avoid leadership roles"},{"label":"B","text":"Physician + Clinical Leadership Development (AAMC + AAFP + ACHE)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single workshop sufficient"},{"label":"D","text":"No development needed"},{"label":"E","text":"Random advancement"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Physician + Clinical Leadership Development (AAMC + AAFP + ACHE): (1) **Need**: healthcare transformation requires clinical leadership; complex change management; alignment of clinical + business + patient interests; (2) **Leadership competencies**: - **Self-awareness + emotional intelligence**: Goleman framework; - **Vision + strategic thinking**; - **Communication** — written, verbal, presentation, listening; - **Influence + negotiation**; - **Team building + management**; - **Change management** (Kotter 8-step, others); - **Financial + business acumen**; - **Quality + safety**; - **Data + analytics literacy**; - **Diversity, equity + inclusion (DEI)**; - **Mentorship + sponsorship**; - **Conflict resolution**; - **Ethical leadership**; - **Resilience + wellness**; (3) **Levels of leadership**: - **Self-leadership** (foundation); - **Team leadership** (e.g., medical director small practice); - **Departmental + division**; - **Organizational + system** (e.g., CMO, CMIO); - **National + advocacy**; - **Community + societal**; (4) **Development pathways**: - **Formal education**: MBA, MPH, MHA, MMM (Master of Medical Management), certificates; - **Leadership development programs**: ACHE, ACPE, AMA, specialty (AAFP, ACP); - **In-house programs**: organization-specific; - **Mentorship + sponsorship**: critical for advancement, especially women + URM; - **Project management training**: PMP, Lean Six Sigma; - **Coaching + executive coaching**; - **Self-directed learning**: books, podcasts, online; - **Stretch assignments** + cross-functional roles; - **Boards + committees**: medical staff, hospital, specialty society, community; (5) **Leadership development at all career stages**: - Trainee — chief resident; - Early career — clinical lead, project lead, committee; - Mid-career — director, MD-administrator dyad; - Senior — executive, board; (6) **Specific challenges**: - **Physician-administrator tension**: dyad leadership models; - **Burnout intersection** with leadership; - **DEI + representation gaps** — efforts to develop diverse leaders; - **Generation differences**; - **Imposter syndrome**; - **Work-life integration**; - **Compensation transition** from clinical to administrative; (7) **Leadership during disruption**: - COVID lessons in healthcare leadership; - Adaptive leadership (Heifetz); - Crisis communication; - Sense-making + ambiguity; (8) **Servant leadership + others-focused**: align with primary care values; (9) **Quality improvement + clinical leadership**: PDSA, Lean, Six Sigma; lead through QI projects; (10) **Patient-centered + community-engaged leadership**: PFAC engagement, community partnerships; (11) **Equity-focused leadership**: address structural racism, social determinants, diverse workforce; (12) **Resources + organizations**: - **ACHE** (American College of Healthcare Executives); - **ACPE** (American College of Physician Executives); - **AAFP Leadership Institute**; - **AAMC** (Association of American Medical Colleges) leadership programs; - **Harvard, Cornell, Penn, others** executive education; - **NLN, AONL** for nursing; - **Boards specific**: women, URM-specific (e.g., NMA); (13) **Coaching profession growing**: ICF certification; executive coaches with healthcare expertise; (14) **Multidisciplinary**: physicians + APPs + nursing + administration + quality + finance + IT + HR + patients + community + boards

---

Physician leadership: needed for transformation. Competencies (emotional intel, vision, communication, change mgmt, financial, DEI). Levels + pathways (formal degree, programs, mentorship, projects). Career-stage development. Specific challenges. Equity-focused. Resources. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — developing physician + clinical leadership in primary care + healthcare organizations';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No policy engagement"},{"label":"B","text":"Healthcare Policy + Primary Care Advocacy (AAFP + ACP + AAP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Random advocacy"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid politics"},{"label":"E","text":"Single legislation knowledge"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Healthcare Policy + Primary Care Advocacy (AAFP + ACP + AAP): (1) **Major US healthcare laws + frameworks** (international context note): - **Social Security Amendments 1965**: created **Medicare** (federal — 65+, disabilities) + **Medicaid** (federal-state partnership — low income); - **Children''s Health Insurance Program (CHIP)** 1997; - **Affordable Care Act (ACA) 2010**: - Insurance marketplaces (Healthcare.gov, state exchanges); - Medicaid expansion (states optional — varies); - Pre-existing condition protection; - Dependent coverage to 26; - Preventive services covered without cost-sharing (USPSTF A + B); - Essential health benefits; - Individual mandate (penalty zeroed 2017); - Subsidies; - Quality + delivery innovations (CMMI); - **MACRA 2015**: MIPS + APMs (value-based); - **HIPAA 1996**: privacy + security; updated post; - **HITECH 2009**: EHR adoption + Meaningful Use; - **CARES Act 2020**: COVID response; - **Inflation Reduction Act 2022**: drug price negotiation Medicare; - **No Surprises Act 2020/2022**: out-of-network billing protection; (2) **Coverage gaps**: - **Uninsured ~ 26 million** (post-ACA but persistent); - **Underinsured** (high cost-sharing); - **Coverage cliff** vs Medicaid expansion holdouts; - **Immigration status restrictions**; - **Mental health + substance use coverage**; (3) **Drug pricing + access**: - IRA Medicare negotiation; - 340B program; - Drug shortages; - International comparisons; - Generic + biosimilar; - High-cost specialty + biologics; (4) **Primary care policy priorities** (AAFP, ACP, AAP, AOA): - **Payment reform**: shift FFS → value-based, primary care primary payment increase, hybrid models; - **Workforce**: GME funding, scope of practice, loan repayment, pipeline; - **Practice transformation**: PCMH + team-based + behavioral health; - **Workforce diversity** + URM pipeline; - **Mental health integration**; - **SDOH** + community-based; - **Health equity** + disparities; - **Administrative burden reduction**: prior authorization, documentation; - **Rural + underserved**; - **Telehealth** post-PHE; - **EHR interoperability**; - **DEA + controlled substance** (X-waiver removal 2023); - **MOUD access**; - **Reproductive + sexual health**; - **LGBTQ+ + transgender care**; - **Climate health**; (5) **Public health system + funding**: chronic under-investment; emergency response (COVID lessons); CDC + state/local health departments; (6) **Global health + international comparisons**: - **Universal coverage** systems (UK NHS, Canada, Germany, etc.); - **US** mixed public-private, fragmented; - **Outcomes** worse vs cost in US; - **Maternal mortality** rising US; - **Health inequities**; (7) **Equity policy**: - **CMS health equity** strategy; - **Structural racism** addressing; - **SDOH** in policy; - **Maternal health** disparities (Black 3-4x); - **LGBTQ+ protections**; - **Disability rights** (ADA); - **Voting rights + civic engagement** as health policy; (8) **Climate + environmental health policy**: - Clean Air, Water, environmental justice; - Climate adaptation + mitigation; - Health sector emissions; - Healthcare without Harm; (9) **Reproductive + sexual health policy** post-Dobbs 2022: variable state laws; abortion access; contraception; sexual education; (10) **Advocacy + civic engagement**: - **Professional associations** AAFP, ACP, AAP, AOA, AMA, specialty; - **Federal**: Congress, agencies (CMS, FDA, HHS, HRSA, CDC); - **State**: medical societies, legislature, governor, public health; - **Local**: city/county, school boards, community boards; - **Coalitions**: cross-specialty, patient groups, public health; - **Direct patient impact**: SDOH addressing, community partnerships, voter registration in healthcare settings (NoHealthyWithoutVotes); (11) **Skills for policy engagement**: - Understanding legislation + regulation; - Communication with policymakers; - Op-eds + media; - Testimony; - Coalition building; - Research + evidence translation; (12) **Resources**: AAFP Advocacy, ACP Health Policy + Advocacy, KFF (Kaiser Family Foundation), Commonwealth Fund, Health Affairs, NEJM Catalyst; (13) **Multidisciplinary advocacy**: clinicians + administrators + patients + community + public health + policy + legal + academia + media

---

Healthcare policy: major laws (Medicare/Medicaid, ACA, MACRA, HITECH, IRA). Coverage gaps. Drug pricing. Primary care priorities (payment, workforce, mental health, SDOH, equity). Public health funding. Global comparisons. Equity + climate + reproductive. Advocacy skills. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — healthcare policy primary care + key legislation + advocacy';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single life stage focus"},{"label":"B","text":"Women''s Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care"},{"label":"C","text":"Random screening"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid mental health"},{"label":"E","text":"Refer everything to specialty"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Women''s Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care: (1) **Family medicine well-positioned for women''s lifespan care** — continuity across stages; (2) **Reproductive years**: - **Preconception health**: optimization 3+ mo before — folate 400 mcg (4 mg if NTD risk), chronic disease optimization (DM, HT, thyroid, mental health), medication review (teratogen replacement), vaccinations update (MMR if non-immune, varicella, COVID), lifestyle (smoking, alcohol, weight, nutrition, exercise), genetic carrier screening, mental health, IPV screen; - **Contraception**: comprehensive options + LARC counseling + risk-benefit + medical eligibility; - **Reproductive autonomy + decisions**; - **Infertility evaluation**: starts after 12 mo (6 mo if > 35), basic workup PCP + refer REI; - **Menstrual + gynecologic**: PMS/PMDD, dysmenorrhea, AUB, dysfunctional bleeding, endometriosis, fibroids, PCOS; - **Sexual health**: function, dyspareunia, libido, sexual orientation, education; - **STI screening + prevention + treatment**; - **Cancer screening**: cervical + breast; (3) **Pregnancy + postpartum**: - **Antenatal care**: comprehensive routine + risk-based; - **Hypertensive disorders pregnancy**: preeclampsia, gestational HTN, chronic HTN; surveillance + management; **Future CV risk marker**; - **Gestational DM**: screening + management + postpartum follow-up + lifelong T2DM risk; - **Mental health pregnancy + postpartum**: high prevalence; screen + treat (SSRI, therapy); postpartum psychosis emergency; PPA; - **Substance use**: screening + treatment; tobacco, alcohol, opioids (MOUD); - **IPV**: screen; pregnancy + postpartum high-risk window; - **Postpartum 4th trimester** (ACOG 2018): comprehensive ongoing care; (4) **Midlife (40s-50s)**: - **Cancer screening**: breast (lower age), cervical, colon (45+), skin; - **CV risk assessment**: ASCVD; lipid; BP; DM; metabolic syndrome; - **Bone health**: foundation for osteoporosis prevention; calcium + vit D + weight-bearing; - **Mental health**: depression + anxiety high in midlife women; perimenopausal mood symptoms; - **Sexual health**: ongoing; menopause approaching; - **Perimenopause**: 4-8 yr transition; irregular menses, vasomotor symptoms beginning, mood, sleep; (5) **Menopause + postmenopause**: - **Symptoms**: vasomotor, GSM, sleep, mood, cognition, joint, sexual; - **MHT** (see separate — NAMS 2022) — < 60 yo or < 10 yr from menopause symptomatic; transdermal preferred; - **Non-hormonal options**: SSRI, gabapentin, fezolinetant new, lifestyle, CBT; - **Bone health**: DXA at 65 (younger if risk); FRAX; treat osteoporosis; - **CV**: lipid + BP + DM + ASCVD risk + statin; - **Cancer screening continued**; - **Sexual health**: GSM treatment (local vaginal estrogen safe even in BC history); ospemifene, prasterone; - **Cognitive aging**: lifestyle + monitor; - **Pelvic floor**: incontinence, prolapse — PT first-line; - **Mental health**: ongoing; (6) **Older adults (65+)**: - **Geriatric considerations**: see separate; - **Cancer screening individualized + life expectancy**; - **Osteoporosis management** ongoing; - **CV ongoing**; - **Cognitive screening** Mini-Cog/MoCA; - **Falls assessment + prevention**; - **Polypharmacy management** Beers; - **Caregiver role** common; - **Advance care planning**; (7) **Common across lifespan**: - **Mental health**: depression + anxiety higher in women across lifespan; trauma + IPV; - **Autoimmune disease** higher in women; - **Migraine** higher; - **Body image + eating**: lifespan; - **Caregiving + family**: integrate; - **Health equity + disparities**: maternal mortality (Black 3-4x), heart disease (often underrecognized in women), other; - **Reproductive justice + access**: lifespan; (8) **LGBTQ+ + gender-diverse**: affirming care across lifespan; (9) **Cultural humility + diverse populations**; (10) **Multidisciplinary integrative team**: family medicine + OB/GYN + breast + REI + endocrine + cardiology + behavioral health + nutrition + PT (pelvic floor) + social work + community + family + caregivers

---

Women''s lifespan integrative: family medicine well-positioned. Preconception → pregnancy → postpartum → midlife → menopause → older adult. Reproductive, cancer screening, CV/bone, mental health, sexual health across stages. Equity + disparities focus. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้หญิงอายุ 35 ปี — primary care across women''s lifespan; preconception → pregnancy → postpartum → menopause planning';

commit;
